						<div class="postbody">I'm pretty much a newbie to &quot;advanced&quot; programming on Windows. I was better on the Amiga back in the days. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br />I'm curious, how are you guys generating the audio in your NES emulators on Windows? The Amiga had 4 soundchannels that could be manipulated in realtime (which made NES audio emulation, well, not that hard anyway).<br />But things work differently on my PC obviously. Audio has to be rendered to a buffer and then played?<br />I am no soundexpert at all, but doesn't that seems a bit difficult when generating NES audio? You really have to know what you're doing concerning samplerates/frequencies etc.<br />Or is there a shortcut?<br />I've checked out some blip_buf.dll but that was obviously not for mortals like myself.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://nes.goondocks.se/">http://nes.goondocks.se/</a><!-- m --></div>
